9. Runtime pipeline

The canonical runtime is six-stage.

Stage 1 — Seed

Capture the charged narrative.

Examples:
	•	“The Garden grows what is repeatedly tended.”
	•	“We are building a cathedral, not a chat log.”
	•	“Luck is coherence under variance.”
	•	“Every artifact must earn its memory.”

A good seed is:
	•	memorable
	•	directional
	•	generative
	•	translatable into behavior

A bad seed is:
	•	vague
	•	ego-inflating
	•	unfalsifiable
	•	resistant to revision

⸻

Stage 2 — Translation

Convert narrative into operational meaning.

Example:

Seed: “The Garden grows what is repeatedly tended.”

Operational translation:
	•	attention is a growth variable
	•	neglected ideas decay
	•	repeated revisiting drives compounding returns

This stage prevents pure aesthetic drift.

⸻

Stage 3 — Ritualization

Bind the translated meaning to repeatable behaviors.

Examples:
	•	revisit top three live ideas each morning
	•	prune one dead branch weekly
	•	ship one artifact per cycle
	•	log one prediction against reality per day

In this framework, “ritual” means stable behavioral encoding, not occult practice.

⸻

Stage 4 — Evidence

Define how reality will arbitrate the narrative.

Possible measures:
	•	output rate
	•	consistency
	•	reduced confusion
	•	decision speed
	•	project continuity
	•	trust and cooperation
	•	stress reduction
	•	measurable domain outcomes

The metric must match the domain.

⸻

Stage 5 — Selection

Evaluate the narrative after lived contact with reality.

Allowed decisions:
	•	Promote — narrative improves action and survives checks
	•	Revise — narrative has signal but translation or behavior is flawed
	•	Retire — narrative is compelling but nonproductive or distorting

⸻

Stage 6 — Compression

Store surviving signal in reusable form.

Compression targets:
	•	symbolic summary
	•	operational rule
	•	associated metrics
	•	failure notes
	•	domain reuse tags
	•	temporal change signature

This output is handed to EchoFrame and optionally promoted to Money Bin.

